SUBJECT: How can Ideaflow maximally benefit from NLP+LLMs
CONTENT: Hi Jacob My name is Anirudh and I heard about Ideaflow from Hari Prasadh, with whom I've worked with to design and develop Interfaces for¬†TfTs. When I saw your profile, I knew I had to reach out and say hi.  I love the ethos behind Intelligence Amplification, especially in contrast to modelling it as a Second Brain. I think it's vital in this new era of AI for humans to massively upskill ourselves lest we find ourselves made redundant. At the same time, it is by using ML/NLP/LLMs optimally that we can achieve such rapid gains..¬†  My research focus over the last 2 years has been tuned towards how careful and precise applications of these SuperIntelligent But Very Dumb Tools can augment and enhance human learning on a potentially exponential¬†level. The usage of these tools in this space can go far beyond summaries and rephrasing, essential though they are.¬† ¬† ¬†Here's a sample interface we built for Roam Research some years ago:¬†¬†https://youtu.be/5sKlLK7QuMI?si=Sf_f5CDbXZ-_DDWy ¬† There are many tangents associated with this space that I think we can have a very interesting discussion about, do let me know your availability. Some topics of my interest: Ethical Gamification, Learning Trees, Augmenting & Enhancing Memory, and I'm sure you'll have your own list :) Furthermore, I believe that I can contribute immensely to Ideaflow at this stage, as someone who has studied the problem space as well as the LLM oppurtunity¬†space. Dear¬†Jacob,  Hope all is well. I would like to share more information about our scientific approach at Inventurist with you.  How is Inventurist different?  Current AI models (e.g., LLMs) learn about the world similar to how humans learn to ride a bike or play tennis. The learning is implicit and can't be explained to other people how it‚Äôs done. That's why kids don‚Äôt need to understand physics before learning how to ride a bike! That's why people can't explain how they can ride a bike without falling down unless they learn physics -- the principles of gyroscopic effect, steering dynamics, etc.    In contrast, the learnings of Inventurist AI are explicit like learning about science or mathematics. Inventurist AI learns about the fundamentals of a business domain by making sense of relationships between growth signals and their cause and effects. The 'sensemaking' ability of Inventurist AI automatically captures the what, the how, and the why in a way that can be explained and verified by people.  What is the value of Inventurist's differentiation?  By synthesizing and maintaining explicit AI models of growth drivers in an industry or a business domain, Inventurist AI can make predictions about future opportunities and risk factors ‚Äì and provide the supporting evidence behind those predictions. Our customers use models built by Inventurist AI to run what-if scenarios and receive prescriptive recommendations about growth opportunities and risks in their business domains. Inventurist‚Äôs AI models are not black boxes.  Why now?  Automatically constructing and maintaining explicit AI models have not been possible before. Manually building such models was as expensive, time-consuming, and complex as teaching people new skills (such as skills for analyzing growth opportunities in a business domain). With Inventurist's Sensemaking AI we are now able to emulate humans' explicit learning capabilities and automate building and maintaining such models on a massive scale and with a lightning speed!  What proof points do we have? We have a working platform in production with backtesting capabilities, customer and investor testimonials, and a growing sales funnel.   Please let me know if this is of interest and if you would like to have further discussion.    Thanks, Gil

I am Grant Holton an amateur whisky drinker & fan, visiting COP, and am joined by Richard Martyn-Hemphill , Food and Farm Tech News Reporter at AgFunder.   Richard will be at the The Piper Whisky Bar St. George Square Glasgow , Thursday evening, 11 November, 19:30 BST to host the in-person social event.   Unfortunately I was tested positive for COVID and I am isolating in my flat till next weekend so will join by Zoom.  https://us02web.zoom.us/meeting/register/tZAlf-CpqjIiG9zDPAnKfhalZSXZHT5fNBYH    - even if are attending the in person event - please register here with zoom. we can then send the list of sustainable whiskies and other articles about this topic.  I thought it would be fun to compile a list of sustainable Scottish Single malts .these are the whiskies on offer at the PiperWhisky Bar tonight - The Bruichladdich Organic 2009 The Ardnamurchan Yamazaki 12yr Tomatin 12 yr  If whisky is not your drink, please feel free to have a beer, wine, coffee or tea.   Let's have a great tasting evening and catch up towards the end of COP26!  Grant and Richard  #COP26Whisky #COPWhisky #COPConnect

CONTENT: First day in Glasgow could involve walking with Urgenda.nl group on their The CLimate March to Glasgow - https://theclimatemiles.nl/en/  I will hopefully meet them tomorrow morning and walk to Glasgow. Looking forward to this.  They leave tomorrow 8:30 from  Ibis hotel Cumbernauld  (meet 8.00 )  For those that can speak Dutch - https://www.linkedin.com/feed/update/urn:li:activity:6859500945693257728/    or follow me on instagram for #COP26 updates: https://www.instagram.com/expatcricket/  something to start at #cop26glasgow  #cop26  from @UrgendaNL   "Join us on our walk to Glasgow!     6-29 October 2021  From Groningen (the Netherlands) we will walk to Glasgow, where the United Nations Climate Change Conference (COP26) will take place. This edition is of crucial importance.   Although the year 2030 might seem far away, we only have 9 years left to limit global warming to 1.5 degrees and reduce greenhouse gas emissions to net-zero. We‚Äôve already reached 1.1 degrees, and the effects are clearly visible. To keep our planet habitable we need to drastically accelerate action. "    We have a project with them to plant 1,5M trees in the Netherlands and they would like others to take this globally - meerbomen.nu which country is next. from Nov till March - how many trees can we save  and transplant?  #sustainavistas

CONTENT: Bobby and all those on the Global Water Call - I was thinking aboutyou on this walk yesterday at the Amsterdam Waterleidingduinen¬† A historic environmental water purificaiton since 1853 in Amsterdam The Netherlands -¬†Enjoy Dutch Autumn  - Enclosed¬† are some of our photos from a walk yesterday in Amsterdamse WaterleidingDuin (please check it out for yourselves) - If you enjoy your deer wildlife October is rutting season of the Dama Deer - a great opportunity to get close up.   WaterLeidingDuinen is where Haarlem, Amsterdam (66% a year)¬† & Den Haag get the majority of their fresh drinking water - 70M cublic litres a year.   https://www.waternet.nl/en/service-and-contact/tap-water/waar-komt-ons-drinkwater-vandaan/amsterdamse-waterleidingduinen/  unique way to get fresh dinking water.   https://thewaterchannel.tv/thewaterblog/the-dune-water-machine/

CONTENT: Save the Date! Tue 28 Sept 18:00-19:30 CEST 17:00 (BST)  Join us for a lively discussion on The Human Cost of the Supply Chain - HRDD!   Daniel Sch√∂nfelder, htps://https://lnkd.in/gtaYyAFd a lawyer in BHR with German law firm Schweizer Legal, will present the new German Due Diligence Act (HRDD) and what it means for companies, NGOs and Right Holders. Article on Recognising NuancesMandatory Human Rights Due Diligence in Mexico and Colombia  https://lnkd.in/g5C4UaQJ  Arjan Udding (https://lnkd.in/gVRJrbYP) & Andrea Rusman From the Impact Institute (Spin-off True Price) - a social enterprise that empowers organizations and professionals to realize the impact economy. They will present & discuss how to gain insight in environmental and human rights violations in company supply chains and into the drivers for change using their Social Scan and the impact of HRDD.   https://lnkd.in/gVKWSFUn  - Social Scan & Impact Assessment examples in Agri, Food, Apparel & other industries  https://lnkd.in/gpnpTzAn                                                                             Hosted by Lasse Kowalewski                            Please register for sustainavistas panel discussion on human rights in supply chains and learn how we can ensure that human rights will be protected.   https://lnkd.in/gQb8S9MS #supplychain #HRDD #humanrights #Humandrightsduedilligence #duedilligence #impact #sustainavistas #humancostofsupplychain

CONTENT: Carbon sinks & offsetting Our planet‚Äôs main natural carbon sinks are plants, the ocean and soil. Over the past half-century, plants and soil have consistently absorbed about 30% of carbon dioxide emissions, even as those emissions increased by 50% over that period. Oceans have also helped, soaking up more than 20%.  Unfortunately, our carbon sinks are under pressure with the Amazon now releasing more carbon than it absorbs. This means that we can no longer depend on some of the world‚Äôs largest carbon sinks to help absorb growing emissions.  Join us for a lively discussion and learn how sustainability professionals and businesses can help to protect and support ‚ÄúCarbon sinks‚Äù.  This interactive panel discussion will offer a practical guide on how different ‚ÄúCarbon Sinks & Offsetting‚Äù measures work and how we can support them as an individual and/or business.  Our guests: Rebekah Braswell COO and Founder Land Life Company  Megan Cayten Chief Commercial Officer Oceans 2050  Ivo Degn Founder Climate Farmers  We look forward to an interactive session.  Please use this Zoom link to register for the event: https://us02web.zoom.us/meeting/register/tZMlcuqorzovHdEO7M6aCIFQNXGChTEMk5BY Tue 25/5 14:15-15:45

CONTENT: Looking forward to our #systemschange call at noon pst today     Also, after some interaction with ecosystems Jim Rutt has instigated, I drafted the below which I thought I'd relay to you all:    I‚Äôm a ‚Äúsolar punk‚Äù. To embrace solar punk means seeking to get to a future that is an apex of our wishes in as realistic a path as possible as quickly as practical. There are as many dimensions of our collective hopes for the future as are imaginable in our extremely neuro-diverse world. Each person‚Äôs specific form of interdisciplinary understanding can bring new ideas and fresh social innovations into the world and help shift us into a new future. Any given mind represents a unique key to unlocking a future in which extraordinary capabilities are unleashed for collective benefit. . It‚Äôs the best way I know to get to a future I care about ‚Äì one that is aligned to a panoply of collective wishes, goals, and hopes.        Unique combinations of capability matter. The Ikigai principle emphasizes the importance of seeking the overlap between what you are exceptional at, what you love doing, what the world needs you to be doing, and what is rewarding for you to do. Everyone can better align themselves with their ideal portfolio of roles‚Äîand when that happens, the unique blend of their skills and passions can have extraordinary impact.        At CrowdDoing we call this process of deconstructing and customizing a person‚Äôs or an organization‚Äôs role and sharing it with other collaborators via ‚Äúrole fracturing‚Äù. We call adding contiguous dimensions to align with a person‚Äôs ideal role ‚Äúfunction stacking‚Äù. Both are possible at vast scales for individuals, institutions, or coalitions. Offering indviduals this improved portfolio of alignment can allow systems change initiatives stewarded by our ecosystem to have transformative potential.        We‚Äôll be evaluating our success as a network based on whether our cherished but challenging aspirations become more feasible. Let‚Äôs be solar punks together.

CONTENT: üôã‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è thanks again for last Friday's chat about so many different topics. Maybe worth exploring next week: The intersection between Solarpunks (creativity, utopia, sustainability) and Systems Thinking/Innovation seems promising. I'd be happy to explore potential projects - for example, Henning, a friend of mine, wrote a mission report about the no man's land between Hamburg and Berlin (180miles) - with a clear hint towards creating sustainable mini-eco systems featuring wind or solar fueled wood-based homes. With the rise of autonomous vehicles (see Tesla's Berlin factory) and awesome tiny house companies from Estonia (like Koda) and Shell's billion-dollar fund for sustainable energy solutions, there might be a sweet spot to realize utopias.

CONTENT: Jacob, there are lists,¬†https://mathworld.wolfram.com/UnsolvedProblems.html,¬†https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Category:Lists_of_unsolved_problems,¬† etc. But the importance of an unsolved problem is also key- not all are equally important. Not all that is unsolved is solved. I think of systems change as often solving problems people didn't realize were problems but once solved unleash the potential fo the community to address their collective challenges. Not all of the problems of the world are formal problems in theory. Heuristics such as Moore's law is not a problem solution or a proof in and of itself but a singularity navigation/uncertainty navigation/asymptote navigation tool nonetheless. Systems change problem solving is where we get aspirations to be more feasible with grace. Fermat's last theorum was an important problem to solve for theory but not all problem are equally connectable to addressing shared value concerns of climate change, bio-diversity collapse, upward mobility gap,etc.

CONTENT: Thank you @Karl Sjogren. With regard to appealing the the 1/3 of the public that is "persuadable," I suggest aspirational storytelling is key... because in my own life that is what enabled me to escape a family dynamic that mirrored the "war against the truth" that exists in America, the UK and other nations today.¬† My father was a malignant narcissist (like Trump). And while that meant no debating his reality was permitted, in the privacy of my own bedroom I found alternative ideas/role models in what I saw on television. My 2016 HuffPost essay celebrated the power of Star Trek to guide people's thinking in a positive direction (including giving them the strength to "refuse to imagine losing"). My essay attracted the attention of @Dr. Lorien Pratt¬†(an AI expert specializing in #DecisionIntelligence) as an example of the importance of external influences that help us ask the right questions.¬† I invite this community to consider planning to use storytelling (including reaching out to Hollywood as part of the plan) to reach a critical mass of the public regarding just how radical a systems change is actually possible (as well as needed). For those who want to read it, here's my 2016 essay...  https://www.huffpost.com/entry/oblivion-or-utopia-star-t_b_11919110

CONTENT: https://medium.com/in-search-of-leverage/in-defense-of-theory-part-ii-why-product-market-fit-is-the-wrong-mental-model-for-systems-ed6a7113ee6c "As a new investment logic designed to catalyse sustainability transitions in the real economy, TransCap is a radical departure from current finance orthodoxy. It challenges the core of our financial system, calling for the adoption of new paradigms, structures, and practices along all stages of the investment process. TransCap is a very different approach than what mainstream financial institutions are accustomed to. As a consequence, my lived experience of talking to big-brand investment professionals is characterized by blank stares and awkward pauses. I sometimes have to cut entire elements from the narrative to not turn off my audience, and I have yet to find a mainstream financial institution willing to engage with TransCap in a meaningful way. Clearly, there is no ‚Äúmarket‚Äù for this ‚Äúproduct‚Äù yet. On an emotional level, this is frustrating. But on a rational level, I have come to understand that a weak product/market fit is exactly what‚Äôs needed for systems innovation."

CONTENT: A thought to offer on the exchange.¬† My view on social change mirrors politics. One third of the population at large will support an approach and one third will oppose it. The game is the get the support of the persuadables that comprise the remaining third. Parts of our discussion created an imagery of a debate about human nature. The references to our better nature led me to think we need to consider how pursuit of self-interest is the counterweight, and its hard to see how those two views can find a way to cooperate. Steve Brant's reference to Naomi Klein's rhetorical question--"What kind of people do we want to be?"-- illuminates a possible way forward, a way to appeal to the persuadables. Experiments that test this idea, I think, should begin on a small scale. Where they succeed, they have potential to fuel larger changes.  That's due to the power of another social quality--the tendency to imitate what works.

CONTENT: we have an interesting event live NOW today 17:00-18:30 CET  on Alternative currency & system change. including an example from Africa.   Money is a powerful instrument which impacts not only our economies but also our thinking. We know how to work with money. But do we really know how money works?  sustainavistas is excited to announce our special webinar ‚ÄúAlternative Currencies and Systems Change‚Äù.  We are going to explore: - Our current ‚Äòunsustainable‚Äô financial system. - Why alternative currencies can benefit the economy and reduce inequality (with existing examples). - How we can correct the flaws of the current system and the potential role of sustainability professionals.  Join us on Tuesday, 23rd February at 17:00 CET to discover why diversity in currency systems will be more beneficial for people, the economy and the planet than our singular money system.  Our distinguished guests: Sarah Bird, CEO of Timebanking UK Brett Scott, Senior Fellow of Finance Innovation Lab Amber Bieg, Chief Marketing Officer of The Joule Case Will Ruddick, Founder of Grassroots Economics  REGISTER HERE: https://bit.ly/3aODgNV  Looking forward to seeing you!

CONTENT: How can we do we achieve solidarity with our future selves? We can identify with our interests, our narratives, and our context. I hope that in the future we'll get to enjoy the context that we¬†get to live in a world in which more people can work on what they love. Likewise, may that be a world in which the SDGs and beyond have been achieved.¬† We have wishes and we have super-powers. Collaboration is the super-power. Our collaboration gap can overcome any learned helplessness we feel individually facing the future. We have transformational agency in autonomy collaboratively but not in isolation. Autopoiesis is a goal of our co-conspiratorial dialogue summoning¬†imagination and instigating integration.¬†Let's be in cahoots¬†for systems change here today at noon pst.¬†#systemschange meet.google.com/azg-fenv-htq Join by phone ‚Ä™+1 505-738-2987‚Ä¨ PIN: ‚Ä™345 674 821‚Ä¨#

CONTENT: Hi folks, so sorry I haven't been able to engage in the conversations or calls lately, my Fridays have been dominated by meetings to help prepare for a multi-part unconference which is kicking off tomorrow! I was inspired by Grant's great share above to invite you all to have a look, as well. It's called CoLiberate: Unconference of Black and Brown Entrepreneurs for Social Justice, and is rooted in the belief that the transition to the next economy here in the US must be led by Black and Brown communities. At the same time, you'll see that we've created space for ally entrepreneurs as well as ecosystem-builders, who may or may not identify as Black or Brown. Whether you're able to attend, make a financial contribution, and/or simply share it here on LinkedIn, I'm grateful for all of it and for the work you all do in the various corners of our world:¬†https://www.coliberate.us/

CONTENT: Looking forward to speaking with you all at noon PST today for #systemschange.meet.google.com/azg-fenv-htq  Join by phone ‚Ä™+1 505-738-2987‚Ä¨ PIN: ‚Ä™345 674 821‚Ä¨#  What is your ‚Äúdrakes equation‚Äù for systems change? What is your ‚Äúdrakes equation‚Äù for getting to a solar punk world? Building a feasible road to a possibility can be achieved via the metaphor of  ‚Äúdrakes equation‚Äù development. Even if we fail to build a road but just build a river we can white water raft down to a solar punk world I‚Äôd be totally happy. So in that spirit I thought I‚Äôd share my initial quick thesis from half an hour thinking about it might go something like:    SIRR * IC *ILNIP * PSI* ERPR* ARD* OSG* SICR* SIICVDAO= Systems change rate corresponding to solar punk world arrival time.    Acceleration of the rate of social innovation replication rate,  (SIRR)  Acceleration of the rate of interdisciplinary citation (IC)  Integration of inter-disciplinary learning, narrative, and impact potential (ILNIP)  Acceleration of the rate of participation in social innovation (PSI)  Acceleration of the rate of stakeholders early responsibility for preventing their risk through the provision of social innovation (ERPR)  Diversification of the impact goals that affect us, to include the aspirational realistic across dimensionalities (ARD)  Integration of outcomes achieved with stakeholders gratitude feedback loops  (OSG)  Social innovation clustering rate proportionate to shared aspirations (SICR)  Social innovation iteration rate proportionate to context variation by design anticipatory omniscience  (SIICVDAO)    For those of you not familiar,  ‚Äú N= The number of civilizations in the Milky Way galaxy whose electromagnetic emissions are detectable.  R*= The rate of formation of stars suitable for the development of intelligent life (number per year).  fp= The fraction of those stars with planetary systems.  ne= The number of planets, per solar system, with an environment suitable for life.  fl= The fraction of suitable planets on which life actually appears.  fi= The fraction of life bearing planets on which intelligent life emerges.  fc= The fraction of civilizations that develop a technology that produces detectable signs of their existence.  L= The average length of time such civilizations produce such signs (years).  ‚Äú  https://www.seti.org/drake-equation-index

CONTENT: Wow, fascinating link Yangbo-¬†https://www.partnerism.org/#cornerstones-page. Thank you Sara,¬† and thank you Jessica. Re "Peace with nature dividends"- this is an interesting way to reference solar punk goals with current culture tools. The technology of imagination for understanding and seeking "dividends" is so over-developed in post-modern capitalism that it could be useable infrastructure for the solar punks. Why not have our yearning for the dividends of peace with nature help us end the civil war on spaceship earth reflected by our present bio-diversity crises?

CONTENT: Karl, jessica@rinova.co Bobby I'd love to see more about the peace with nature dividend. Indeed we must become stewards. We are at the point of a tectonic shift from individual-first to collective first. CONTENT: Thanks Tanuja. I love the quote of " In 1911, Frederick Winslow Taylor, the efficiency expert, wrote "In the past the man has been first; in the future the system must be first.‚Äù". I was going to share one part of a conversation I had this week. Think tanks are either realistic but not aspirational enough, or they are aspirational without being realistic. Hyper-aspirational, hyper-realistic as the Pareto optimality equivalent for systems change makes sense to me. Pinchot Index (https://www.amazon.com/Pinchot-Impact-Index-Measuring-Aggregating/dp/0692396519) identifies risk and impact reward. Maybe all the stakeholders could champion systems change based on their peace with nature dividend? They talk about post-war dividends. If we are too often at war with nature rather than in collaboration with nature, can we create the prospect of the peace with nature dividend to drive global adoption of our strategic narratives?

CONTENT: Apropos our discussion about excessive financialization, here is an article from The Atlantic from 2017 "How Money Became the Measure of Everything"  Some key points from the article are: - capitalism was born in the mid-19th century as a result of increasing capitalization - it was crucial to the rise of economic indicators -¬†by the mid-20th century economic indicators that focused on monetary output came to be seen as apolitical and objective -¬†In 1911, Frederick Winslow Taylor, the efficiency expert, wrote "In the past the man has been first; in the future the system must be first.‚Äù -¬†By the early 21st century, American society‚Äôs top priority became its bottom line, net worth became synonymous with self-worth, and a billionaire businessman who repeatedly pointed to his own wealth as proof of his fitness for office was elected president.   https://www.theatlantic.com/business/archive/2017/10/money-measure-everything-pricing-progress/543345/

CONTENT: @Saskia Verraes, thx for bringing up the contra-argument. I agree with @Yangbo Du, NLPC seems to be a spurious publication. However, the research paper that it mentions is not spurious, so I will use it as a comparison to the NYT article.   I read the introduction, background and conclusion (not the mathematical portions yet) of the research paper. Its analysis is based entirely on shareholder benefits as represented by stock price, and not on stakeholder benefits.  Therefore it is not speaking to the same things as the NYT article.  Stakeholder primacy was ‚Äòinvented‚Äô in order to avoid the ills of shareholder primacy; such as the continuing increase in wealth-gap, and, growth-based business models that are causing devastation of the environment. From a systemic view, shareholder primacy is like a group of friends purchasing an SUV, then saying: ‚ÄúWe only care about the benefits/losses to the people who invested in the SUV, and not to anyone else; even though we are using the same roads, the same air, the same supply chains, and the same petroleum as everyone else.‚Äù  The question ‚Äúwhether doing good is good for business‚Äù has a simple answer, in my opinion. Every business benefits from a stable society and a dependable environment: that is where they get both their employees and customers from. Therefore, healthy society and environment are resources for every business. Therefore, businesses must show responsibility towards the resources that they consume. In financial terms: businesses must pay the cost of the resources that they consume.  The paper says ‚ÄúESG expenditures generate insufficient returns and hence reduce shareholder value‚Äù : if we now add the ‚Äòresource consumption‚Äô model I mentioned above to the calculations of returns -- it should be quite clear that, even if returns remain in the same ballpark as for non-ESG companies, ESG companies are consuming (or destroying) less resources therefore their overall value is higher.  All of the mathematical analysis, such as in Fig 2 which indicates that ESG only contributes 3% to the stock‚Äôs performance -- is a reductionist analysis. Is it even valid for complex adaptive systems?  A strong supporter of ESG investing is Hiro Mizuno (link below), former exec at Japan‚Äôs 1.4 trillion dollar pension fund GPIF. His talk is worth listening to: ‚Äúat the end of the day as a community, asset owner owns the capital market so we need to make the capital market more sustainable, and for the capital market to be sustainable, society must be sustainable and for all the society to be sustainable environment must be sustainable‚Äù.  Here, in this Systems Change group, we are in the business of changing what business does in terms of its social/environmental impact footprint. Aren‚Äôt we? We should attempt to have a clear analytical/theoretical basis for this goal. Hiro Mizuno (again) lays it out clearly in the 2nd link below.  https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=63POCdfQDbM  https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JwtpKVgFPyY&t=51s

CONTENT: We have used slack in ten of our crowddoing groups. I'm also in some with Saskia on Whatsapp. We have also used linkedin groups. What i like about linkedin threads is it has strong personal identification so people are likely to find each other, and may connect. Linkedin groups is ok for that, but has very negligible reminders when there are new comments. Each person is also limited in the number they can have so it becomes difficult for all to reserve one spot for us without leaving another group to make room. We have a google group for this already, i can reinvite anyone not in it if that helps. Or we can establish whatsapp, or linkedin group, or alternative channel. Other friends have suggested telegram or signal.¬† Slack is good in some ways, feels impersonal in others. LinkedIn keeps a limit of 50 people in the messenger group. I have a longer list invited to the series on Fridays but I try to only add to this thread those who have participated in our live discussions.

CONTENT: Just wanted to appreciate @Saskia Verraes, @Yangbo Du and @Tanuja Prasad especially your commentary about financialization and how it also ties to gender equity hits it right on the head - why is the argument that women should be able to fully participate in the workforce centered on the idea that we can all make more money off of them? Not exactly a feminist point of view. And, bringing this around, I actually had a chat with a vegan the other day who argued that feminism and veganism are inseparable - she couldn't reconcile, in her words, taking a mother's milk and eggs (and supporting male chicks being killed because they don't produce eggs) and still being feminist. I'd never thought about it that way, and I suspect a lot of folks would call that a stretch, but it definitely gave me pause and made me reevaluate how those values intersect for me.

CONTENT: If you ask former director of IMD Dominique Turpin, he would argue that the 40-some CHF per kilo for beef the Swiss pay is a fair price (and yes, animal welfare is better than that in neighbouring Germany, where beef costs half as much per kilo).  One can readily make the ethical argument that the most sustainable option is to raise however many animals necessary to maintain ecological balance and slaughter as few animals as possible (favouring beef cattle and other large hoofed mammals raised as purely free range). The implication is that meat from livestock will be a luxury product or at best a side dish instead of a main course, with plant-based or lab-cultured alternatives an option for those who still feel entitled to cheap meat.

TO: Michael Critelli,Pete De Mare,Robert Fishkin,Jacob Cole,Jim Rutt,Sara Olsen,Stacey Sude,LinkedIn Member,Claudia Akel,Peter Leyden,Saskia Verraes,Latif Nathani,Colin Campbell,Jacques (Jaap) Verraes,Sarah Hayes,Gary Starr,Pedro Paulo Lins e Silva,Chris Gagn√©,Rajinder Jhol,Manuel Manga,Gardner Bickford,Michael Kleeman,Peter Coughlan,Tomas Carruthers,Chuck Brookhart Brown,Juliette Devillard,Steve Waddell,LinkedIn Member,Fyodor Ovchinnikov,Marty Matlock,üåø Nicole Lazzaro üïäÔ∏è,Karl Sjogren,Tom Watson,LinkedIn Member,Yesha Bavishi,Nikhil Dugal,Gil Friend,Claudia Hutten,Chinedu Echeruo,Nick Gogerty,Will Hogan,Grant Holton,Bob Spoer
CONTENT: @Chuck Brookhart Brown:¬† I agree.¬† In a classic case of systemic response, the cost of manufactured meat forced the price pressure down to the animal-farming level causing them to keep animals in appalling conditions and feed them appalling things in order to raise productivity. Which, again in a systemic fashion, came back to haunt us in terms of health impacts.  Have we forgotten how the hormones given to cattle has reduced the age of puberty *by several years* of girls particularly in poorer regions?¬†  We need broader discussion on "financialization": how using finance metrics for everything has skewed them into becoming industrial production lines.¬† Even in gender equity discussions, McKinsey produced a widely-distributed report on the trillions of dollars that the economy is losing by not having women participate fully in the workforce. Thus measuring women only as producers of units of work.¬† The role and presence of women in all walks of life has a real qualitative effect that is absolutely essential. Using money as a metric hides that.

TO: Michael Critelli,Pete De Mare,Robert Fishkin,Jacob Cole,Jim Rutt,Sara Olsen,Stacey Sude,LinkedIn Member,Claudia Akel,Peter Leyden,Saskia Verraes,Latif Nathani,Colin Campbell,Jacques (Jaap) Verraes,Sarah Hayes,Gary Starr,Pedro Paulo Lins e Silva,Chris Gagn√©,Tanuja Prasad,Rajinder Jhol,Manuel Manga,Gardner Bickford,Michael Kleeman,Peter Coughlan,Tomas Carruthers,Juliette Devillard,Steve Waddell,LinkedIn Member,Fyodor Ovchinnikov,Marty Matlock,üåø Nicole Lazzaro üïäÔ∏è,Karl Sjogren,Tom Watson,LinkedIn Member,Yesha Bavishi,Nikhil Dugal,Gil Friend,Claudia Hutten,Chinedu Echeruo,Nick Gogerty,Will Hogan,Grant Holton,Bob Spoer
CONTENT: I've been vegetarian for almost 20 years now but I eat as little processed food as possible and not a fan at all of the new "meat alternatives." But I don't think they were meant for us, either - we made these choices based on ethical grounds more than anything else. This may be controversial, but it might also be helpful to know that many of us believe that future generations will look back in shock and disbelief that we so casually manufactured the slaughter of billions of animals *every year* to consume cheap, medicated meat products. It's a profound moral failure that very few people talk about. But going back to Saskia's question, I don't necessarily think we will or everyone should give up eating meat - systems change doesn't mean everyone has to adopt my lifestyle. Rather, going back to sustainable cultivation and consumption, regenerative agriculture, that feels like the proper equilibrium.

CONTENT: Might Impossible Foods or Beyond Meat qualify as acceptably "vegan" if zero animals were harmed in manufacture? CONTENT: The responses above are excellent evidence of the value of or even need to take a distributed, diversity approach to system change.  Perhaps in light of them my response here is a little harsh, but the argument being put forward by the 'idealists' is , in my experience, used often when people are in a position of relative power,  even unconsciously don't want to lose their position. SUBJECT: Frustrated you aren‚Äôt progressing faster in business?
CONTENT: Hey Jacob  In tech we are taught that if you are perfect, you will be successful.   You need to make the perfect code because if there‚Äôs a bug and something goes wrong, it could cost you thousands of $$$!  For building apps, features, designs ‚Ä¶ all of this is where perfectionists thrive  Yet 8 years ago, I had a realisation when I was completely overwhelmed in my tech business‚Ä¶  What made me awesome in one area doesn‚Äôt equate to success in other areas.   I took the framework of being perfect and tried to apply it to running my business.  The challenge is that it ended up creating more problems because ‚Ä¶ I didn‚Äôt know where to focus I was stuck in cycles of overthinking  And ended up procrastinating on big decisions  I didn‚Äôt want to make a mistake and appear like a failure, yet it was a self fulfilling prophecy.   Since understanding this, my team and I have helped over 400+ tech entrepreneurs to let go of the wheel ie perfectionism/control   So they can put their business on autopilot and double their business revenue.   If you‚Äôre struggling with this too, drop me a message saying ‚Äúpurfectionism‚Äù and I‚Äôll share how we can help you too.  If not, no worries I hope you keep crushing your business either way! Warmly  Ben

‚Ä¢ One key difference between Roam and what we are building is that Roam structurally doesn't support labeled relations. Instead, their links are more like links in a wiki. So with Roam you can't, for instance express:  Bat Manson former engineering manager at: Apple  And then pivot back to Apple and see:  Apple former engineering managers: Bat Manson, Jane Doe, Joe Schmoe  This structure is essential to building the ‚Äúmultigraph‚Äù behavior and the larger scale vision of an ‚Äúintelligence augmentation layer‚Äù for your browser. It‚Äôs also one of the reasons our product can build a network effect and become an essential information access platform instead of being yet another collaboration tool teams might choose to adopt in a one-off way.

‚Ä¢ It feels pretty validating to see an idiosyncratic product in this space garnering interest from both intellectuals and operators. Excited about the growth of public awareness of the power of linked information management tools. Our investor Naval Ravikant named 2021 as the year for information management tools. It's a large space: feedback from one of our alpha users who switched from Roam to Ideaflow "I'm not the person Roam was built for."

‚Ä¢ A design principle we think about often, especially as a team with ex-Google/Apple people, is how Chrome edged out Firefox as a browser because they managed to be snappier and more minimalist. We think this quality is essential in building the go-to place people where capture thoughts. It's unclear to me whether Roam is on a trajectory to get this right, or even has a team that could (real time collaborative text editor design is a highly specialized skill, and we have some of the few world experts on our team).  Listening to user feedback, we‚Äôve learned that it is critical to prioritize mid to large scale performance because most avid alpha users have knowledge bases that are at a multi-thousand note scale, and having an instant memory extension they can rely on seems to be the biggest thing people want. (We aren‚Äôt targeting tremendous size yet, e.g. Jerry Michalski‚Äôs Brain, but making sure the basic experience remains slick and snappy for the majority of our target demographic.) Performance is one of the big complaints many information management aficionados have about Roam. Load Time (15K notes): Ideaflow (2 seconds) Video https://share.getcloudapp.com/nOuDojAZ Roam (25 seconds; then further delay to edit text) Video https://share.getcloudapp.com/rRu0Grpx

CONTENT: Hi Jacob,    Fruit Street Health is a leading digital health company that delivers a CDC-endorsed diabetes prevention program through telehealth and live group video conferencing with registered dietitians. Participants in our program participant in group classes with dietitians around topics such as diet, exercise, sleep, and stress management. They receive a wireless scale, Fitbit, and can take photos of their food in our mobile app to get feedback from their dietitian. This helps them reduce their weight, improve their health, and reduce their risk for Type 2 diabetes.    We are currently recruiting advisory board members who believe in our social mission of preventing diabetes and we wanted to know if you would be interested. We are recruiting advisors with experience in areas such as revenue growth, sales, marketing, finance, strategy, or who just believe in our mission and think they can add value as an advisor.   We are currently recruiting advisory board members who believe in the mission of our company and have the skills and experiences that can be leveraged to drive future growth. Responsibilities of advisors include:   -Giving input through an online discussion forum called Basecamp with other advisors on the strategy and growth of the company.  -Joining periodic Zoom meetings in which advisors monitor and guide the company‚Äôs progress  -Making helpful introductions to potential customers or partners.  -Giving the management team guidance as they grow the venture.    If you are interested in joining us on our social mission to prevent millions of cases of Type 2, please reply with your email and phone number and we will send you a link to our advisory board application. Merry merry merry!üéÑüéÅ üéâ Btw In case you're interested, friends and I hosting an impromptu Zoom Christmas party / intellectual salon this weekend! Likely 5:30 pm PT, tomorrow,¬† Sun! Feel free to invite friends! Will be chill!

MIT Media Lab researcher/product designer Jacob Cole and exited YC founder David Greenspan (creator of Etherpad, YC ‚Äò07 as AppJet, sold to Google) have teamed up to build IdeaFlow ‚Äîa notebook that augments your intelligence as you type.  Demo: Post a meeting with Sequoia   Ideaflow is a low friction team knowledge base and data integration tool that acts as an extension of your brain. First launching as a system to augment the intelligence of top tier research teams in finance and strategy, it has the simplicity of a notebook but recognizes known people, companies, and other entities as you type, bringing up all references or connections to them your team or existing knowledge systems have ever made. IdeaFlow enables users to seamlessly capture and stitch together fragments of information, amplifying their ability to solve critical problems.  At the heart of our platform is the concept of rich, graph-based notebooks. Unlike traditional notebooks or wikis, which are centered around pages filled with static, long-form text, IdeaFlow treats entities within pages ‚Äî e.g. people, companies, ideas ‚Äî as first-class objects. This makes it possible to enable users to capture relational information between entities, like a mind map, but without the scaling problems. This is part of what Tim Berners-Lee proposes as the potential for the future of the Web.Ideaflow is currently in private beta, is advised by former Reddit CTO Marty Weiner, had revenue of over $200K from paid pilots last year, and just raised $8M from top angels and VCs, including 8VC, First Round, Sequoia scouts, and Naval RavikantWe‚Äôre a team of 3 full time right now and looking for a few special people to play major roles which will have huge autonomy, creative freedom, and upward mobility. It would be amazing if any of those people can get as excited as we are about curating all kinds of lists of valuable information for the good of the world, connecting related ideas, personal information management/Memex‚Äôs, and generally, fixing the Internet :)  - a JavaScript engineer and an iOS engineer with great product sense to play major roles, who are up to the challenge of helping us build something at least as complex, seamless, and high performance as writing an IDE.  - We're also looking for a fast-typing, warmhearted operations person who is competently and passionately available to do whatever needs to be done do whatever needs to be done, and also could be a strong representative of the company in a context like a career fair. May have the potential to end up director of operations or chief of staff.  - NLP/ML/Web scraping/data integration expert‚Äî ideally familiar with dependency parse trees and has also written an interpreter, e.g. a LISP interpreter, at some point in the past.

Sure!¬† In case you're interested:  a) We're planning to host a deep dive on Ideaflow with a group of interesting intellectuals, investors, and operators either this or next week. Still confirming a time; would Friday 11am or 1pm PT, or Monday 11am or 2pm PT work for you? Happy to set up a call separately as well.  b) Additionally, I will be speaking on the future of Intelligence Augmentation and Ideaflow at the Investing in Startups & Identifying the Rocketship Summit, which is hosting GP's from many top VCs tomorrow, Oct 1st, 2 PM PT to 2:30 PM PT. I think this talk may address some of your questions.  If you'd like to attend, please register at this link with promo code GOOGLEVIP: https://www.eventbrite.com/e/investing-in-startups-summit-sponsored-by-google-svb-salesforce-others-tickets-118126025121   Here's a quick brief for my fireside chat:  MIT Media Lab product designer Jacob Cole has teamed up with Etherpad founder David Greenspan (YC S07, sold to Google) and other veteran entrepreneurs, to build a notebook that augments your intelligence as you type. Ideaflow enables teams of users to seamlessly capture and stitch together fragments of information, amplifying their ability to solve critical problems.  In this discussion, we'll demonstrate how Ideaflow can be used to augment the social intelligence of entrepreneurs and investors, and discuss the emerging field of IA (Intelligence Amplification), which is on a trajectory to becoming a defining entrepreneurial trend of this decade.  Vision: Ray Kurzweil projects that, by 2045, humanity will be hooked up to a "shared neocortex in the cloud" by brain-computer interfaces. We will leave the brain-computer interfaces to Elon Musk, but we believe it‚Äôs possible to build that "shared brain" now, and that it might look different than many imagine. We want to create a future where nobody feels alone with their ideas, where intellectual soulmates find each other, where superconnectors are empowered. We see our software as critical to creating the frame for humans and machines to work together to solve the world's most challenging problems.  Best, Jacob

IdeaFlow‚Äôs founding team includes MIT Media Lab researcher/product designer Jacob Cole and exited YC founder David Greenspan (creator of Etherpad, YC ‚Äò07 as AppJet, sold to Google), and has raised over $8M from top angels and VCs, including First Round, Sequoia scouts, and Naval Ravikant. SUBJECT: MIT intelligence augmentation tools startup
CONTENT: Hi Brad! I saw you recommended by Sam Goto on LinkedIn ‚Äì  I was Tim Berners-Lee‚Äôs research advisee at MIT and am working on a company with David Greenspan (creator of Etherpad, YC ‚Äò07, which sold to Google) building a notebook that augments your intelligence as you type. First launching as a tool to augment the intelligence of elite knowledge work teams solving critical problems, it enables users to seamlessly capture and stitch together fragments of information, amplifying their ability to solve critical problems.   We‚Äôve just raised over $8M from top angels and VCs, including First Round, Sequoia scouts, and Naval Ravikant.  We are right now working on tracking down a special sort of person with significant JavaScript experience who is up to the challenge of helping us build something at least as complex as writing an IDE. This person would hold a major role that can potentially can offer tremendous creative freedom and an opportunity to build the ultimate personal information management system. There is also the opportunity to do a lot of interesting machine learning (especially NLP/computer vision) work.  We deeply believe that what we are doing is on the critical path to unlocking the potential of the Web to vastly amplify humanity‚Äôs collective intelligence.   Demo: Post a meeting with Sequoia https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4feZo9PqTlo  Please let me know if you‚Äôre interested ‚Äì ideally email me at a jacob@ideaflow.io

One key Verizon executive estimates that at least 40% of the work in the company is repeated either because new projects were started without full knowledge of what is already being worked on or because there were already related projects across multiple companies that Verizon has acquired. Moreover, the problem is not just that work is being duplicated ‚Äì people within a company who have worked on or are working on related projects often have resources or expertise that could greatly accelerate or support each other.    IdeaFlow is a shared brain for organizations, a platform to connect people to related ideas and relevant resources from within their own organization. This was part of the original vision for the Web, which can now be realized with the support of modern AI.    IdeaFlow is a Silicon Valley-based company that came out of research at MIT with Sir Tim Berners-Lee, creator of the Web, has raised $1.8M from notable investors including the CTO of Reddit and the director of the MIT Media Lab, and is currently in beta with industry-leading companies.

http://ideaflow.io/  We're a startup from MIT working to unlock the potential of the Web as a medium for collaborative problem solving.  We‚Äôve begun by launching a human-AI hybrid platform for teams of analysts in financial industries to integrate business ecosystem data from multiple sources (e.g. Pitchbook, Crunchbase, internal CRMs), recognize references to the same people from across these databases, and visually explore the resulting knowledge graph. Users can further enrich this graph with missing information through an ultra-low friction notetaking interface and by importing internal spreadsheets, resulting in a ‚Äúshared brain‚Äù for the entire organization.   We see this as the first step of the larger project of creating a platform for collaborative cognition, which many see as the ‚Äúhybrid car‚Äù of automated cognition. IdeaFlow is lightweight, enterprise and consumer-ready implementation of the sort of smart personal/group knowledge base system AI thinkers have dreamed about across the decades, from Vannevar Bush‚Äôs Memex <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Memex> to Niklas Luhmann‚Äôs Zettelkasten <https://takingnotenow.blogspot.com/2007/12/luhmanns-zettelkasten.html> to Tim Berners-Lee‚Äôs Giant Global Graph <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Giant_Global_Graph>.  IdeaFlow has raised $1.8M from notable investors including the CTO of Reddit and the director of the MIT Media Lab, and has several industry-leading companies as beta SaaS customers, including a $200K/year deal with Silicon Valley Bank.

However, more time passes, and DApps, at least as they are conceived by the Ethereum community, still have not found a breakthrough use case. We believe that another conception of DApps, which we call ‚Äúvertically decentralized applications‚Äù, have even greater potential, and in fact will be how the majority of applications on the Web are built in the future.   We believe that the Ethereum and related communities so far think of DApps in too limited of a sense. They focus on the creation of what we call ‚Äúhorizontal DApps,‚Äù apps that distribute symmetrically across all nodes ‚Äì for instance, systems such as decentralized exchanges or messaging apps. We believe there is even greater potential in another class of DApp, the  "Vertical DApp."  ‚ÄúVDapps‚Äù are applications which have the different layers of their data processing (and even UI) stacks decoupled and outsourced to third party service providers.  Now, you might ask: isn‚Äôt this what  already happens when we build apps that use APIs? The answer to this is yes. However, the revolutionary power of VDapps lies in the fact that, unlike in a monolithic application,  the API‚Äôs a VDapp uses are not set in stone by the original app developer, but instead can be swapped out at runtime by the end user with any other API that conforms to the same input and output standards.    Consider a developer building a VDapp that needs to use an API to perform Named Entity Recognition, a common natural language processing task.  Instead of specifying that the app will use a particular API for this, such as AlchemyAPI or the Intellexer API, developers will simply write a placeholder component that links to the standard for named entity recognition modules. Then the end users‚Äô application, at runtime, will select a current and appropriate API that  satisfies  this standard.  We expect a number of third-party API reviewing services to emerge, and for VDapps to automatically select the highest rated API per one of these services.     This is good for application developers, consumers, and, most of all, API developers. In traditional monolithic applications,  it is dangerous for developers to use  all but the most stable of third-party APIs because it is out of their control whether an API is going to remain alive in the future, change its price, or change its interface.   When API‚Äôs change,  applications simply break, and  the original developers  must scramble to  update all the applications they have that use them.  Often, they never get to this, and, with traditional monolithic application architectures, third-party developers  have no ability to step in to help. Often, applications simply break ‚Äì For instance, Firechat, the app that helped the Egyptian revolution, no longer works, because a it called internally shut down.  In short, monolithic architectures makes it difficult, if not impossible, to create software that can last for decades without constant maintenance by the original developer.  This is revolutionary for API developers. It introduces a powerful new market dynamic ‚Äì previously, an API developer who builds a better OCR library, for instance, needs to market this library to developers and convince them to switch, which is a tremendous amount of work. But in the future that we are creating, the moment an API reaches the highest spot on a popular ranking site, it will have millions of users instantaneously.  The natural way to implement payments for API calls made over this protocol is a token. This token will act like a universal AWS API credit that applies to all APIs

When API‚Äôs change,  applications simply break, and  the original developers  must scramble to  update all the applications they have that use them.  Often, they never get to this, and, with traditional monolithic application architectures, third-party developers  have no ability to step in to help. Often, applications simply break ‚Äì For instance, Firechat, the app that helped the Egyptian revolution, no longer works,  because a it called internally shut down.  In short, monolithic architectures makes it difficult, if not impossible, to create software that can last for decades without constant maintenance by the original developer.   The natural way to implement payments for API calls made over this protocol is a token --  interested in your thoughts as to which token has the lowest transaction cost these days. This token will act like a universal AWS API credit ‚Äî you buy credits for one API but these credits are usable across all APIs   The free market is arguably the most successful technology ever designed for mobilizing human collective intelligence. Where market dynamics are able to operate freely and rapidly, we see the fastest innovation and the most efficient delivery of value to society. By contrast, in industries where there is vertical lock-in and little modularity, innovation stagnates.  From airline booking websites to the touchscreens in cars, where  there is no space for free market competition, we see stagnant technology. By contrast, consider the touchscreens on android phone handsets -- they are very high quality ‚Äì because they are a modular component and there is direct competition unfettered by lock-in through vertical integration we think our new paradigm for software development may produce as large a jump in productivity as that between innovation in the automotive UX space and innovations in phone handsets.  Because applications are locked together by vertical stacks of technologies, a third-party developer who builds a better component at any specific level of the stack, if they want their component to be used or be commercially successful, must do the hard work to build an entire app, or discover and market to the developers of each of these existing apps. Even in the best of cases, with developers who are the most competent marketers of their technologies, it often takes years for an innovation to penetrate the ecosystem fully, if ever it does.  Since there's no standardized protocol for specifying API‚Äôs inputs and outputs ‚Äî and this which APIs' are interchangeable with each other ‚Äî it's impossible to build apps this way, even if a developer wanted to. Fixing this will be one of the implications of our protocol and token project succeeding. We believe the majority of applications built in the future will be constructed this way.  An example of how IdeaFlow is a great breakthrough use case of this: A frequently requested third-party extension to IdeaFlow.io (our main non-token data integration / company knowledge base platform) is an extension that can read in a photograph of a business card and perform OCR (optical character recognition) to identify the name of the person and the company.  A second extension that has been requested is one that can read in a photo of a table full of multiple business cards, split them into individual business cards, and scan them in. We would like the latter developer to be able to release just their specialized service, and not have to make a commitment about which OCR API to use as the second processing step. However, more time passes, and DApps, at least as they are conceived by the Ethereum community, still have not found a breakthrough use case. We believe that another conception of DApps, which we call ‚Äúvertically decentralized applications‚Äù, have even greater potential, and in fact will be how the majority of applications on the Web are built in the future. We believe that the Ethereum and related communities so far think of DApps in too limited of a sense. They focus on the creation of what we call ‚Äúhorizontal DApps,‚Äù apps that distribute symmetrically across all nodes ‚Äì for instance, systems such as decentralized exchanges or messaging apps. We believe there is even greater potential in another class of DApp, the "Vertical DApp." ‚ÄúVDapps‚Äù are applications which have the different layers of their data processing (and even UI) stacks decoupled and outsourced to third party service providers. Now, you might ask: isn‚Äôt this what already happens when we build apps that use APIs? The answer to this is yes. However, the revolutionary power of VDapps lies in the fact that, unlike in a monolithic application, the API‚Äôs a VDapp uses are not set in stone by the original app developer, but instead can be swapped out at runtime by the end user with any other API that conforms to the same input and output standards. Consider a developer building a VDapp that needs to use an API to perform Named Entity Recognition, a common natural language processing task. Instead of specifying that the app will use a particular API for this, such as AlchemyAPI or the Intellexer API, developers will simply write a placeholder component that links to the standard for named entity recognition modules. Then the end users‚Äô application, at runtime, will select a current and appropriate API that satisfies this standard. We expect a number of third-party API reviewing services to emerge, and for VDapps to automatically select the highest rated API per one of these services. This is good for application developers, consumers, and, most of all, API developers. In traditional monolithic applications, it is dangerous for developers to use all but the most stable of third-party APIs because it is out of their control whether an API is going to remain alive in the future, change its price, or change its interface. When API‚Äôs change, applications simply break, and the original developers must scramble to update all the applications they have that use them. Often, they never get to this, and, with traditional monolithic application architectures, third-party developers have no ability to step in to help. Often, applications simply break ‚Äì For instance, Firechat, the app that helped the Egyptian revolution, no longer works, because a it called internally shut down. In short, monolithic architectures makes it difficult, if not impossible, to create software that can last for decades without constant maintenance by the original developer. This is revolutionary for API developers. It introduces a powerful new market dynamic ‚Äì previously, an API developer who builds a better OCR library, for instance, needs to market this library to developers and convince them to switch, which is a tremendous amount of work. But in the future that we are creating, the moment an API reaches the highest spot on a popular ranking site, it will have millions of users instantaneously. The natural way to implement payments for API calls made over this protocol is a token. This token will act like a universal AWS API credit that applies to all APIs

CONVERSATION TITLE: Technology Selling in the Age of Agility
CONTENT:
Hi Jacob


Global disruptive events have accelerated the world of B2B technology buying into an era we call the Age of Agility.


When we surveyed close to 6,000 tech buyers globally, we found that they are buying technology differently now:


  • 63% of the tech buying decision is influenced by non-IT functions
  • 44% of buying journeys extend beyond one year
  • 2 in 3 buyers hesitate to try a new vendor unless sellers demonstrate greater value
  • 57% of tech buyers prioritise post-sale support


We've identified 4 trends to help tech sellers like you to thrive in today's changing world.


  1. Multi-thread beyond the IT function
  2. Place Buyers First in a long customer journey
  3. Address your buyers' paradox of needs
  4. Seize the post-sale frontier

Get all the insights in our latest report.


Download Technology Selling in the Age of Agility!


Best regards,


Michele Tan

Marketing Manager

LinkedIn Sales Solutions

CONVERSATION TITLE: MIT Alums, Why Now is the Time to Start Investing in VC
CONTENT:
Hi Jacob,


I am the Managing Partner of Castor Ventures and an MIT ‚Äò88 grad, reaching out to fellow alumni as we raise our fifth venture capital fund for MIT alums and friends. 


By now, you have likely heard of Castor Ventures. In short, we invest together in a diversified portfolio of ~30 hard-to-access venture deals. We are a community and VC fund for individual investors like you, not for institutions or the ultra-wealthy. 


Whether you are already familiar with Castor or not, here are four reasons why now might be the time to begin investing with us:


  • Taking Advantage of Low Valuations: 2021 is following the pattern of other recession years; valuations of venture-backed companies are low. VC does require patience, but it‚Äôs very advantageous to be getting in at low valuations.
  • Innovation: Technology trends like remote work, telemedicine, and autonomous vehicles are re-writing the economy. We are actively investing now in the next generation of companies that will be shaking up the landscape 3, 5, 10 years from now.
  • The COVID Effect: The companies that thrive, succeed, and win in the new post-COVID world are likely to be nimble, aggressive, and well-funded for growth. Many will be venture-backed. We intend to invest in the best of those.  
  • Combating Volatility: VC is a 10 year, optimistic asset class that believes in the march of innovation. Venture capital has outperformed the S&P over many periods*, in particular during downturns in the economy.


My team and I are thrilled with the investment opportunities we are seeing (the deal flow). If you are interested in learning more about investing with Castor Ventures, or simply wish to join our community of 25k MIT alumni and friends to follow our progress, I‚Äôd be happy to connect. 


Click the link below to get the conversation started today. I look forward to speaking with you soon.


Sincerely,


Chris Sklarin, MIT ‚Äò88

Managing Partner, Castor Ventures

chris@castorventures.com
